# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — AI Operating Guide

This file explains how to behave in this repository. It is intentionally
short and stable — it is not where project knowledge lives. It applies to
any coding agent working in this repo (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, or
otherwise) — this is the file coding agents read by convention, so
project-wide behavior belongs here, not duplicated per tool.

**All long-term project knowledge — vision, architecture, standards,
roadmap, decisions, open questions, and history — lives in
[`docs/ai/`](docs/ai/README.md).** Start there. `docs/ai/README.md` indexes
every document and maps common task types to the file that's relevant, so
you don't need to read the whole directory for every task.

## Workflow Expectations

- Before starting non-trivial work, check `docs/ai/README.md` for the
  doc(s) relevant to what you're touching.
- When you learn or decide something durable — a new architectural
  decision, a shipped feature, a corrected assumption, a newly scoped
  feature — update the relevant file in `docs/ai/` directly, not just local
  memory. Local memory (e.g. Claude Code's auto-memory) is per-machine and
  invisible to other sessions, machines, or agents; `docs/ai/` is what keeps
  everyone in sync.
- Don't duplicate documentation. If something is already recorded in
  `docs/ai/`, update it in place there — don't restate it here or in a new
  file.
- Make targeted edits only. Don't perform unrelated rewrites, renames, or
  reformatting outside the scope of the current task, even if you notice
  something worth improving — note it in `docs/ai/open-questions.md`
  instead of acting on it unasked.
- Before considering a change done, run this project's checks — see
  `docs/ai/coding-standards.md` for the exact lint/typecheck/test/build
  commands — and fix what they surface.
- When a request is ambiguous or a decision has consequences beyond the
  current task, stop and ask rather than guessing. If you proceed on an
  assumption, record it in `docs/ai/open-questions.md`.
- Never fabricate sources, test results, or completion status. If something
  wasn't verified, say so.

